node.text: Well... why not cram a bunch of great activities into one day? Most years I am in New Zealand this time of year but figured I would do one of my old Birthday Traditions- the Trifecta of activities- Ski, Shed Hunt, Fish. I also like to run a mile as fast as I can and do a couple memory tests just to see where I stack up from years past...haha. It feels like a good barometer. Was pretty fun, figured I might as well share it.

node.text:
There is no better meat on the mountain and no more exciting bowhunting challenge than chasing elk during the rut. This video takes you along on a successful self-filmed longbow hunt, giving tips through the whole field to table process. This video is in collaboration with the release of my playable character in theHunter: Call of the Wild Video game, to share real life hunting tactics straight from the field.

@thehunter_cotw #learntohunt #huntergatherer #bowhunting #solohunter #livewildhunthard #cuttingthedistance

node.title: How to Bowhunt Elk- A self-filmed longbow hunt

Tips and tactics for getting started hunting from the pursuit to the dinner table. This hunting how-to gives you the basics to hunting one of North America's most widely hunted game animal... the wild turkey.

This video is part of a sponsored collaboration with theHunter: Call of the Wild Video game @thehunter_cotw to introduce its players to hunting strategies for those interested in taking the leap to hunting in real life. They have found that a large portion of its players have never hunted but are interested in trying.

It is awesome to hopefully give them enough info to get in the field and give it a go. For those that already hunt I hope you enjoy the chase aspect of the video and watching a hunt come together.

In conjunction with the video, I am excited to announce that I am a character in the new, Call of the Wild reserve I will be giving real hunting tips and stories in-game. If you want more info as well as a special discount go to the link in my bio or at www.remiwarren.thehunter.com

#livewildhunthard #learntohunt #thehunter #callofthewild

node.text:
Advanced backcountry butchering. Eight years ago, I showed a boned out quarter on Solo Hunter TV that was hangable. It is just the way I had always done it. However, I did not realize that very few people knew the trick to de-boning a hind quarter to leave it hangable. This is a must-watch field butcher video. You need to know this. I made this video a few years back and for some reason never shared it until today. Make sure to tag someone who needs to learn this trick!

This goes perfect with my new Cutting the Distance podcast episode that dropped today on hot weather meat care. If you don't subscribe to it, now is the time! I promise it will make you better in the field! Also, I will be sharing more like this on Youtube, so find my channel. These videos tend to get blocked here on IG and Facebook, so please share this with fellow hunters if you see it before it gets blocked out. I know there are a ton of you that asked specifically for this!

And as always thanks for the support! This technique can also be done with a front shoulder as well. If you want me to make that video, let me know and I will get one going!

#livewildhunthard #cuttingthedistance @gerbergear #hellotrouble #butchering #meatprep #deboning #backcountrybutcher #wildmeat #huntergatherer @solohntr @meateater

node.text:
Garbage Bag Waders: One piece of gear I always have is a couple of contractor grade garbage bags. The primary purpose is to use as a pack liner when packing out meat to not blood soak my pack, but I really like items with multiple uses. 

I use them a lot for things like stream crossings by running them over my boots and under my gaiters. Then tying into my belt loops.

Some other great uses include stuffing with branches for a sleeping pad or extra insulation if camping in the winter.

I have also used them to save time melting snow by  filling with snow and putting in the sun during the day to melt into a bottle set up below while I am away from camp.

Oh and they are also great for garbage.

node.text: Backcountry Gear Quick Tip: I wrap my trekking pole and water bottle with some duct tape to store it so it is easy to find. If I cut myself or need to fix something, I don't have to dig around for it. This has come in handy a few times to quickly close a small wound. I also replace some zipper pulls with D-loop cord and will even use the draw string on my tent bag as a replacement drop-away rest cord if I need to make a repair.

Great stalk, great self filming, bad final execution. When I look back at this I wonder what would have happened if I waited longer to stand. 

In the moment, I felt like I was making the right move. I drew out of sight and thought I could raise up and get a shot. Also I could not fully see the deer from where I was drawing, I did not know he was as keyed into me. As he stood from his bed I lowered down and drew back.

Hindsight is always 20/20 I could have easily waited and watched him bound off then reviewed the replay and wish I would have tried raising up. I have had both work and both go wrong. That is what makes bowhunting so addictive.

#velvetweek #muledeer #westernhunter #archery #bowhunting #solohunter

Summer scouting can be a super effective way to see what might be in an area by capitalizing on deer that will be bachelored up in the high country feeding. 

Quick unplanned scouting trips based on weather changes are always fun. I will thow some glass and essentials in a  #yetibag and hit the road. 

The only summer scouting downside is the heat. When I see a break in cooler weather, I try to mobilize. During this temperature change you will catch more movement longer in the mornings and evenings. 

It gives you a better chance to find deer out in the open and pinpoint productive areas to focus on for the season. 

#livewildhunthard #scouting @yeti

Tarantula: One of the best bulls I have taken. I wanted to do a series of posts focusing on velvet. No better way to kick off Velvet Week than with a giant velvet bull. 

This was a early tag that started in August. There was a very small window where I could potentially run into a bull that had not yet shed. There are not many opportunities to hunt elk early and I really wanted to find one in full velvet. I ran into this bull opening day but messing with my camera to film was just long enough to lose him in the thick timber.

Six days later I reconnected with the bull I referred to as Tarantula. If you want to read the full hunt story, I posted an article I wrote right after the hunt on my blog. There is also some video of the trip on my IG story.

#livewildhunthard #velvetweek #elkhunting #cuttingthedistance #huntergatherer @federalpremium
